SIMPLE: fulminate
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fulminate
<hw>Ful"mi*nate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Fulminated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Fulminating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>fulminatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>fulminare</ets> to lighten, strike
with lightning, fr. <ets>fulmen</ets> thunderbolt, fr.
<ets>fulgere</ets> to shine. See <er>Fulgent</er>, and cf.
<er>Fulmine</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To thunder; hence, to make a
loud, sudden noise; to detonate; to explode with a violent
report.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To issue or send forth decrees or censures with the
assumption of supreme authority; to thunder forth menaces.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fulminate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fulminate
<hw>Ful"mi*nate</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause to
explode.</def> <rj><au>Sprat.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To utter or send out with denunciations or censures;
-- said especially of menaces or censures uttered by ecclesiastical
authority.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They <qex>fulminated</qex> the most hostile of all decrees.</q>
<rj><qau>De Quincey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fulminate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Fulminate
<hw>Ful"mi*nate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. P.
<ets>fulminate</ets>. See <er>Fulminate</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety>
<fld>(Chem.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A salt of fulminic acid. See under
<er>Fulminic</er>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A fulminating
powder.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Fulminate of gold</b></col>, <cd>an explosive compound of
gold; -- called also <altname>fulminating gold</altname>, and
<altname>aurum fulminans</altname>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>fulminate of mercury</ent>⟦br⟧
